nary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Whorwood was born in 1325, in Haresfield, Gloucestershire, England, his father, John Whorwood, was 16 and his mother, Mrs. John Whorwood, was 16. He married Margery de Haresfield in 1347, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1378, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1325–1378":"1325–1378","1325–1405":"1325–1405","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1352–1411":"1352–1411","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1378":"1378","1411":"1411","1453":"1453","1310":"131